	title = {Potential {Impacts} of {Future} {Land} {Use} {Change} on {Ecosystem} {Services} in the {Mesoamerican} {Biological} {Corridor}},
	volume = {43},
	url = {http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2019AGUFMGC43L1439H},
	abstract = {NASA signed a joint statement with the general secretariat of the 
Central American Integration System (SICA) in March 2019, following up
an earlier 15-year memorandum of understanding between NASA and the
Central American Commission for the Environment \& Development, a
SICA sub-secretariat. A key goal of the collaboration is increased
application of Earth observation data to protect the region's natural
heritage, including the Mesoamerican Biological Corridor (MBC), which is
home to almost 10\% of the world's terrestrial vertebrate species. The
forests of the MBC also have an important role related to hydrological
regulation. Toward understanding that, a retrospective study (1980-2010)
was done using data derived from satellite resources such as Landsat and
MODIS, and complemented by land use scenario modeling cover the period
2010-2100. The data indicate that over three decades, forest cover
across the region had declined by almost half, from 72\% in 1980 to 42\%
in 2010. Additionally, a 'business as usual' trend in land cover change
would translate to a decline in Central America's forest cover to {\textasciitilde}24.3\%
by 2050. To study the potential impacts of such land cover change on
hydrology, we examined the Samalá River watershed in Guatemala,
home to Guatemala's 2 nd largest population center, and whose
heterogenous landscape is representative of Central America's
watersheds. For that watershed, it was estimated that forest cover fell
from 22\% in 2003 to only 9\% in 2019, a decrease of almost 60\%. Based on
hydrological modeling, it was found that the effect of such drastic
forest cover change resulted in an increase in surface runoff by 7\%, a
corresponding 4\% decrease in groundwater infiltration, but a 31\%
increase in sediment delivery. With the Samalá River being
emblematic of the challenges affecting watersheds in Central America,
the implications of such will be further explored in this talk.},
